 and spent a single year at Albany Law School, never taking a degree. Justice Scalia later called him the best legal stylist of the twentieth century.","number":4},{"number":5,"category":"law","header":"His three-zone map still governs presidential power","body":"In his 1952 concurrence in the Steel Seizure Case, Jackson sorted presidential power into three zones — strongest with Congress's backing, weakest against its will. It became the most-cited separation-of-powers opinion in American law."}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"HD6117","display_label":"married his son William, the Nuremberg lawyer"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"HD6313","link_text":"Melanie Jackson","display_label":"was his granddaughter, the literary agent who represents Thomas Pynchon"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Robert Houghwout","last_name":"Jackson","display_name":"Robert H. Jackson","gender":"male","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Supreme Court justice; chief Nuremberg prosecutor","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781020099/Jackson-Wearing-Official-Ro_mwhnmi.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Attorney","organization":"Jamestown, New York"},{"role":"Assistant Attorney General","organization":"United States","start_year":1936,"end_year":1938},{"role":"Solicitor General","organization":"United States","start_year":1938,"end_year":1940},{"role":"Attorney General","organization":"United States","start_year":1940,"end_year":1941},{"role":"Associate Justice","organization":"U.S. Supreme Court","start_year":1941,"end_year":1954},{"role":"Chief U.S. Prosecutor","organization":"Nuremberg Trials","start_year":1945,"end_year":1946}],"birth":{"year":1892,"country":"United States","month":2,"day":13,"city":"Spring Creek","state":"Pennsylvania"},"death":{"year":1954,"country":"United States","month":